<subSubSection pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Compact cushion-forming undershrub with thick woody taproot, branched at base with short woody prostrate to ascending branches to c. 15 cm, young stems sericeous. Leaves sessile, 1.2-2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.4 cm, linear-oblanceolate, acute, attenuate at the base, sericeous and with some spreading hairs. Flowers solitary, axillary, shortly pedunculate but becoming crowded, sessile and subcapitate towards the branch tips; peduncles 0-5 mm, pilose; bracts leaf-like; bracteoles similar but shorter; sepals 8-11 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 mm, oblong, acute to apiculate, concave, adpressed pilose, not bicoloured; corolla 1.7-2.3 cm long, white with distinct pink, pubescent midpetaline bands, unlobed; ovary pilose; style glabrous, divided c. 4 mm above base; stigmas 4 mm. Capsule and seeds unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Endemic to Turkey (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Rechinger</emphasis>
61014, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Fitz &amp; Spitzenberger</emphasis>
721, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Sorger</emphasis>
s.n. [28/5/1964]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Could be confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stace, Bot. J. Linn. Soc. 64: 58. 1971. (Stace" authorityYear="1971" baseAuthorityName="Boiss." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus boissieri subsp. compactus" order="Solanales" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="boissieri" subSpecies="compactus">Convolvulus boissieri subsp. compactus</taxonomicName>
but the 1-nerved, near linear leaves are distinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Parris, BS" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Turkey" pageId="208" pageNumber="209" pagination="198 - 219" refId="B256" refString="Parris, BS, 1978. Convolvulus. Flora of Turkey volume 6: 198 - 219" title="Convolvulus." volume="volume 6" year="1978">Parris (1978</bibRefCitation>
: 209) treated 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bornm., Repert Spec. Nov. Regni Veg. 5: 168. 1908. (Bornmueller" authorityYear="1908" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus phrygius" order="Solanales" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="phrygius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Convolvulus phrygius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sa'ad" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus pulvinatus" order="Solanales" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pulvinatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Convolvulus pulvinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as distinct species, they were collected at the same place and the distinctions in measurements are minor. The corollas are similar in size and the sepals are only about 2 mm different in length. There is no good reason to treat them as separate species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
